Data reading¶

The procedure fo data reading was designed to easily throw new recordings and enable or disable without the need to change the code (Every directory used for training should contain the word 'enabled' in its name).

In [3]:
##
# Read the recorded data and create a shuffled dataset
#
rec_dir = 'data'
recording_dirs = [os.path.join(rec_dir, name) for name in os.listdir(rec_dir) if os.path.isdir(os.path.join(rec_dir, name)) and 'enabled' in name]

header = ['center_image', 'left_image', 'right_image', 'steering_angle', 'throttle', 'break', 'speed']

header_dict = {'center_image': 0,
               'left_image': 1,
               'right_image': 2,
               'steering_angle': 3,
               'throttle': 4,
               'break': 5,
               'speed': 6}

dataset = pd.DataFrame()

# Process every directory and read the data in it
for d in recording_dirs:
    print('Processing {}'.format(d))
    tmp = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(d, 'driving_log.csv'), header=None, names=header, comment='#')
    tmp.left_image = d + os.path.sep + tmp.left_image.str.strip()
    tmp.center_image = d + os.path.sep + tmp.center_image.str.strip()
    tmp.right_image = d + os.path.sep + tmp.right_image.str.strip()
    dataset = pd.concat([dataset, tmp])

# Reset index to avoid duplicated index (different files starts with 0 index)
dataset.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)

Processing data/udacity-enabled

Data visualization¶

Here he can see how to data looks like. Some remarkable findinds:

  • The majority of the recorded data is at full speed
  • Also it wasn't recorded while breaking
  • The distribution of angles is kind of normal, with a high peak at 0 angles (which corresponds with the track, where are lots of straight sections)
In [4]:
##
# Display some info about the data
#
def plot_values(dataset):
    # Histogram of throttle
    fig = dataset.throttle.hist(bins=20)
    fig.set_title('Throttle')
    plt.show()

    # Histogram of speed
    fig = dataset.speed.hist(bins=20)
    fig.set_title('Speed')
    plt.show()

    # Histogram of break
    fig = dataset['break'].hist(bins=20)
    fig.set_title('Break')
    plt.show()

    # Histogram of steering angle
    fig = dataset.steering_angle.hist(bins=20)
    fig.set_title('Steering Angle')
    plt.show()

    # Plot of steering angle
    fig = dataset.steering_angle.plot()
    fig.set_title('Steering angle')
    plt.ylim(-2, 2)
    plt.show()
In [5]:
plot_values(dataset)

To improve the quality of the data, speed below 25mph is discarded and also where breaks is higher than 0.1

In [6]:
##
# Filter unwanted data
#

# Low speed (initial images, crashes, etc)
dataset = dataset[dataset.speed > 25]

# Hard breaking (dangerous situations, going off the road, etc.)
dataset = dataset[dataset['break'] < 0.1]

The information used to predict the steering angle is the input from the from cameras. Here some samples of left, straight and right turn are displayed to have a better understanding of data:

In [8]:
##
# Plot some images to visualize the data
#
# Number of images to plot
n_plot = 5

below = dataset.steering_angle < -steering_range
above = dataset.steering_angle > steering_range
zero = ~(below | above)

for ds in [dataset[below], dataset[zero], dataset[above]]:
    for i in range(n_plot):
            fig1 = plt.subplot(131)
            fig1.set_title('Steering angle: {:.2f} ({:.2f} grads)'.format(ds.iloc[i].steering_angle, ds.iloc[i].steering_angle*25))
            fig1.set_axis_off()
            image = mpimg.imread(str.strip(ds.iloc[i].left_image))
            fig1.imshow(image)

            fig2 = plt.subplot(132)
            fig2.set_axis_off()
            image = mpimg.imread(ds.iloc[i].center_image)
            fig2.imshow(image)

            fig3 = plt.subplot(133)
            fig3.set_axis_off()
            image = mpimg.imread(str.strip(ds.iloc[i].right_image))
            fig3.imshow(image)

            plt.show()

plt.imshow(image)

This image is: <class 'numpy.ndarray'> with dimesions: (160, 320, 3)

Some parts of the image are not useful (like the sky and the front of the car). After cutting those sections, the image is resampled in a 32x32 size see if it's possible to distinct where the car should steer to.

In [10]:
low_l = int(0.3125 * image.shape[0])
sup_l = int(0.75 * image.shape[0])
img = image[low_l:sup_l,:]

drivable_shape = img.shape
print('Drivable shape {}'.format(drivable_shape))
plt.imshow(img)
plt.show()

Drivable shape (70, 320, 3)

Since we'll use a LeNet architecture, a 32x32 image is displayed.

We can appretiate that 32x32 conserves the information needed to distinguish the curvature of the road and it's much smaller (will train faster)

The final architecture is LeNet. Here we'll see the summary of the network.

Two dropout layers were added to avoid overfitting, one after the flattened layer and one after the first hidden layer.

ELU activation was used because it was proved by Comma.ai autopilot[1] and it showed a better performance than ReLu [2]

This architecture showed very good results with low data and very low processing power requeriments. Actually it was trained with a CPU computer in less than 15 minutes.

[1] https://github.com/commaai/research/blob/master/train_steering_model.py

[2] https://arxiv.org/abs/1511.07289

Discussion¶

This was the most challenging project in the whole nano degree. Sometimes, I've found that results were counter intuitive and there was not a clear way to improve your model besides trying it on the simulator.

Even though a good advance in finishing the track 1 was made, this architecture needs more work to finish track 2 and to be more robust.

The lesson learned are:

  • Nvidia and Comma.ai architectures need lots of data
  • very good data is key for success
  • Data balance is as important as the quality of the data: very different results were found depending on the proportion of ~0 angles included in the dataset. Final results included ~5% of 0 angle
  • Even small and simple architecture (as LeNet) are good start for complex problems

LeNet was chosen after having tried Nvidia, Comma.ai and custom architectures with poor results. Without much hope, LeNet performed surprisingly well.

Only Udacity data was used on this model given that its quality was by far better than what I could get.

Things that added randomness to the project:

Hardware: this project was quiet hardware dependent. I even tried known working models (tested on GPU) that didn't worked on my setup Data collection: the simulator and the data provided by it sometimes seemed strange, like a straight road and a very high angle (maybe were the images posterior of a big turn)

Instructions¶

The training code could be run as:

python drive.py model.hdf5

Driving could be run as:

python drive.py model.hdf5

Simulator settings: Screen resolution '640x480', Graphics Quality 'Fastest'

How to convert .hdf5 to .json and .h5

python hdf5_to_jsonh5.py model.hdf5

A recording names track1.mp4 is provided to see the car driving on my own setup
